Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: (Spoiler Warning) I like the twist about the bad guy. But I'm still irritated by a lot of the bad guys logic. "War is good because it makes us strong. Piece is bad because it makes us weak." Of course if you're not at war then you don't need to be strong except as a deterrent against future war. Having a strong military to prevent war is very logical. But starting a war to make the country/planet/whatever strong defeats the point. Then there is the fact that the bad guy is a bit of a psycho from being shipwrecked. But I get the impression he became an immortal king of the entire planet overnight. It really doesn't seem like such a bad place to retire on. But more importantly his new subjects had space travel. He could have probably left within the first week if he had wanted to. That part I don't think was ever really addressed.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
*SPOILERS* Well, i finally watched the movie and did not really like it. I mean ok, i enjoy Kirk and co, but the plot was pedestrian at best and i've seen less generic villains in a Power Rangers episode. Both factors were absolute zero, compared to Into Darkness.
And then we get the one-note hot alien babe we're supposed to drool at/feel for and who - sad shocker - likes rap. Did the director think only hare-brained high schoolers would watch this? (with no disrespect to Sofia Boutella.... besides, why even cast her if you won't make proper room in the movie for her dancing skills like Kingsmen did? All we get is some flat, inelegant combat).

And the scene where the alien drones form a literal wave and the Franklin rides it while playing crap music, leaving a trail of exploding enemies behind, complete with the part where the ship flies in the alien drone wave equivalent of the green room?

I really hope they pick someone else to direct the next. Take Douchin Lin and send that sissy boy back to his beach to direct Furiously Dumb 17 or whatever.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: Simon Pegg breathed new life into this series and did a really good job.  I enjoyed it much more than I thought I was going to from seeing the trailers.  It felt like a Star Trek movie should.  The villain was a little bit too much of the tired trope "former ally turns evil and tries to take revenge" type, but Idris Elba at least portrayed him well.  The most enjoyable parts of the movies for me were the character interactions with the crew, though I did also enjoy Jaylah and her role in helping them find the USS Franklin, which seemed like a nod back to the Enterprise series, which I very much miss, so it was nice to see that thrown in.  I was really hoping the villains in this might turn out to be Romulans, which would have added more depth than the "former captain wants revenge on Star Fleet".  I'm really hoping you guys do something with them in the near future, as they were some of the most interesting villains in the franchise and certainly during TOS and TNG timelines.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: As enormous trekker i anticipated this with joy and optimism and while it is not disaster everyone thought it would be it is inferior to last 2 films. Beyond is definitely homage to the more adventurous classic episodes and is geared to broader audiences than last film and i can appreciate the change. Crew is once again amazing and chemistry is off the charts, adventure kicks into 5th gear and never stops, dialogue is witty and fresh and it makes you feel for the characters. It is also exciting, thrilling and always on the edge of your seat entertainment. What bothered me is how Justin Lins directing style doesn't mesh with star trek tradition and how god awful villain in this movie was. I mean the directing was really awful, there were moments where i just could not see what is going on, especially during the dark scenes. As for Krall/Edison it was the most lazy, generic and uninspiring way to go about bad guy and it just did not work. I did not care about him or his agenda. Overall it delivers as fun summer popcorn entertainment and i was satisfied when credits roll plus it was kinda sad when you say goodbye to Leonard and Anton in the end, may they rest in peace. 3.5/5

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: For all those who are critiquing Spock's human tendencies, please remember that they created room for this development by introducing a time traveling Spock who influenced his younger self. His mother originally lived a lot longer until Nero came back in time and destroyed Vulcan. This exposed Spock to his human emotions which, by nearly direct instructions from the original Spock, Kirk exploited to gain command of the Enterprise in the 2009 movie. This Spock has lost his mother and his homeworld at a point in his life where his hasn't had time to build up a strong enough wall to mask his human side. He has also explored a romantic relationship with Uhura during his time of crisis which further opened him up to his emotions. I'm not sure why everyone is so upset about the character development straying from TOS but clearly you're lacking a grasp of the concept of time travel. Introducing that one element into the new series has left all future character development and encounters with TOS villains like Khan to be unpredictable and therefore better able to entertain a new generation and old fans alike by taking us down an alternate timeline. Let's stop hating so much on all the changes and see where this new road takes us. I'm sure Kirk wouldn't mind seeing how his alternate self faired by striking his own path without his father around.

Hello Everyone, I feel I need to post this. For those who might have missed it, due to a fan based film both CBS and Paramount have issued "guidelines" that actually destroy all the possibilities of anymore real fan based trek films in the future. If you would like to know more search for "star trek prelude to Axanar" and watch the previews and details about the show. There are many fan based films for you to watch and some are really good considering they are not made by a real studio. You will even see a few real actors are involved and the efforts have been made to have a very high quality of production. Yes, some not so much but its about Star Trek not production. Now please consider that for many years now they (CBS and Paramount) have allowed a few groups to make many really good (and some not so good) episodes based on Star Trek in many versions as long as they do not "make a profit" from the production. To actual start making the episode Axanar they had a fund drive and made over 1 million US Dollars so, CBS and Paramount sued them to stop production. Recently they released the "guidelines" for all future fan based films that are not only not constitutional points (like actors who worked in any trek canâ€™t work in fan based films and vice a versa) but limit production time and costs in such a way that means no less than a clear effort to kill all fan based Star Trek films. Read the complete set of guidelines here: http://www.startrek.com/fan-films
I ask all fans to get educated on these Star Trek fan based films to read up on this matter. Please learn the facts about the past films and the possibility of future for more of them. If you cannot agree that CBS and Paramount be allowed to force these guidelines on fan film production please help us stop them. Also please compare the way the fan films for Star Wars are treated where they even offer a public awards show for them. I, and other Star Trek fans are calling for a boycott of the upcoming movie and the 2017 series on CBS unless they publicly stop this and provide the fans with a reasonable and legal ability to enjoy others ideas of the Star Trek world. They have allowed it for years but now they are moving to kill them while hoping it wonâ€™t affect them making more money off Star Trek. So, letâ€™s boycott them and stop the money they would make from the 7-22 release of Star Trek Beyond and the 2017 series planned to have one show on TV then the rest on a pay service only from CBS. If they see enough decrease of the upcoming movie sales they will obey us as the fans and workout a real reasonable way for them to continue without the idiotic and illegal current guidelines. I, and more than 20 people I know have agreed to boycott the new film unless this is fixed right. 
Thanks for your time.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: A 21st Century motorcycle in a movie depicting far-out-into-the-future machinery in a far-out-into-the-future time scale? I'll watch it because I'm a die-hard Star Trek fan of the OS, but I'm not very hopeful after watching this trailer. I sure hope it turns out to be better than what this trailer doesn't promise it to be. Maybe it's the trailer that's not so good... I doubt. As for Spock now embracing his "human side," that's just crappy. It ruins so much with Star Trek's OS dynamic of Spock's logical decisions and inability to understand human emotions. If there is life in the universe there just might be species out there who don't feel emotions like we are familiar with. They might be entirely logical in their decision making. What a shame to not have a species like Spock remain Vulcan and logical. That alone makes it "not Star Trek." Producers are losing touch with what Star Trek was all about. IMO

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Destruction! Loud things! Impossible odds! This just screams "formula action movie". This isn't Star Trek at all, it's a video game. 

There are enough Transformers, Fast and Furious, and comic book adaptation movies to keep the adrenaline junkies satisfied. Can't we have one franchise that is just a bit cerebral? Somehow, Hollywood has incorrectly conflated "Intelligent" with "Boring". Do you know what boring really is? Motorcycle jumps. Car chases. Surviving fire and massive explosions by "ducking". 

Action is fine, but every movie franchise seems to want to rewrite the laws of physics and human physiology. Suspension of disbelief only goes so far, and after that it's clear that you've made your characters invincible and immortal, unless you choose to kill one off for shock value. That's really boring. 

There has to be someone who can write and direct something that's a happy medium between Star Trek: The Motion Picture and the rebooted Star Trek: The Running, Jumping and Explosions with Lens Flares.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: I could out-write any Paramount writer in 1 month,  I guarantee that. Yeh, I am a writer, I dont have the big connections, it is annoying to see people get paid a great deal for so little thought. I thought the 2009 one was alright and Eric Bana played his role perfect. These movies are like 5/10 movies to me, I think Nimoy saved the 2009 one along with Pike.  Star Trek is all about intellectual prowess. Not just action, they should of started where Kirk is a Cadet and becomes Captain in the third part of a trilogy. Losing Pike in the third act rather than the second, sometimes it takes a great deal of suffering and many mistakes to become a good leader, not a cocky kid. They seem to just give him everything so quickly and easily, they should of made Kirk feel fully responsible for Pikes death and Spock help him see the logic. Beastie Boys track is kind of stupid, its not essential, if you want to create a reminiscing event, use a similar event with higher stakes, not a song. I guarantee no one will remember that song by that time. This is Star Trek,  not Die Hard, its just a sheer example of an ego getting in the way of development by putting forward things that do nothing to serve the whole story.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
This trailer is a disgrace to Star Trek's legacy. I am willing to make the claim that Star Trek has had a larger impact on our society than any other work of fiction created before or after it, and thus, it deserves so much better than to just become the latest mindless and boring high octane action flick whose sole purpose is to draw in the Fast and Furious crowd and make a mountain of money that would make the Grand Nagus envious.

However, I am still holding out hope that this trailer is just awful (like Simon Pegg says), and the movie itself is more akin to "real Star Trek". But even that hope is holding on by a thread, as this movie was incredibly rushed, is STILL undergoing re-shoots, and the studio producing it allegedly stated that they want this movie to be "less Star Trek-y".

I just want this movie to be over with so we can be done with NuTrek and hopefully move on to real, thought provoking, and inspiring Star Trek in the new series.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
I saw the first of these Star Trek Reboot movies a few years back and swore I would never see another one of them.  Not because of the cast, who did a good job, or the direction, production or action, each of them equally good.  What I didn't like was the fact that they were made at all.
Let me try to explain.  I grew up watching Star Trek TOS & TAS  reruns in the 1970's.  I vaguely remember my dad watching TOS in the 60's when it was on prime time.  TOS and TAS were shows that reflected, commented and addressed the era and issues they were created in:  The 1960's and 1970's.  The characters themselves often were reflecting the people of that era as well and the way they thought, acted and reacted to situations similar to those of those eras .  I can say that TNG, DS9, and Voyager did the same for the 1980's and 1990's as well.
But taking Kirk, Spock and the rest of the crew and totally rewrite the history of the franchise to have characters from the 1960's act, think and react to situations from the 21st Century is not only unfair to those of us who grew up in the 60's and 70's but its unfair to the young people of today.  Us old people(I'm in my 50's) deserve to have our generations historical treasures left alone while the young people deserve to have characters, stories of THEIR own which reflects THEIR era(Today).  I don't mind taking the Star Trek universe onward like with shows like TNG, DS9 and Voyager(Don't even talk to me about Enterprise) but don't rewrite history.  LEAVE IT ALONE!
Now please understand that I'm not blaming the younger generation for this.  The kids today are, as a whole, a good generation with some incredible views on the world.  They also are a source of free tech support to a middle aged man who's smart phone occasionally does something its not supposed to do(LOL).  Its MY generation who's deciding to play it safe by rebooting everything and feeding them recycled mind candy.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
I am 47 years old, disabled, and live alone. I recently rewatched the entirety of TV Trek... It was an AMAZING journey of insight and self discovery. But these movies you are making, Paramount... They just are not what Trek is all about. And that makes me very sad. I accepted the first Star Trek "shoot 'em up" as just a way to get more people involved into the franchise who may not be familiar with it. I gutted the 2nd one's premature use of one of the series' pinnacle villains to basically follow the same underlying premise as Star Trek 2: The Wrath of Khan; just accepting it as the price of having some form of Star Trek that was new. But when I saw a THIRD movie shaping up to be yet another "blow stuff up" Star Trek, it was then that I finally accepted the fact that there must be no one left at Paramount who has any sort of clout that remembers what Trek is all about. It should by learning about ourselves as we embark on that amazing next step out into the stars. While, yes, there may be the occasional blatant rollercoaster ride, for the most part, traditionally it has dared to ask the tough questions in clever ways. And I think that is what I am missing the most here: it's that this Star Trek isn't clever. It seems to just expect me to sit back and oo and ah while it makes references to itself. That is, itself from a time when it really mattered. And now with the whole Axanar lawsuit - and don't get me wrong, Paramount, I can kind of see where you are coming from - I just wonder if Star Trek finally really is dead? And in a day and age where the only real metric of corporate success is measured by growth, ironically it's all about money which is one of the very things that Gene Roddenberry himself had REMOVED from our future! (I'm talking strictly Federation, here) I guess it will stay alive in the hearts and minds of the millions - MILLIONS - still alive who will continue to make amazing fan fiction, which includes movies.

There are few things I really truly need in life and believe it or not Star Trek is one of the things that gets my immobile body out of bed and into my wheelchair each day. Now, here it is the 50th anniversary of Trek...I have made it to this date after growing up with it throughout the years...I have reached this milestone with Trek faithfully by my side in many life events and decisions...and I've found it dying. Please don't let the true spirit of Trek die.

I encourage others to tell their Trek story. Tell the world, and Paramount, what Star Trek means to you and why it's important. Take care, all.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
It's a terrible trailer, trying to woo an audience who doesn't like Trek anyway. The fact that it's the 50th anniversary movie of this franchise makes this trailer not only bad, it's insulting.

Look at how Paramount teased ST 6 for its 25th if you want to see how respect of a beloved franchise is treated. Look at how Dr. Who and Star Wars are treated by people who love and respect the history of a show, and all the talented people who came before them. 

Star Wars gets treated with all the reverence of a visit by the Pope. The Falcon is rebuilt in exquisite detail. Star Trek gets all of its history flushed down the toilet (except they keep reusing everything anyway for lack of an original idea), and we get an Apple store and a brewery for an Enterprise.

Since the ST franchise is now split in two by corporate buyouts - movies are made and owned by Paramount and Trek TV is owned by CBS/Viacom, we faithful Trekkies may have to give up on the film franchise. Hopefully the new series by CBS (who took the time and effort to restore TOS with new effects and do a frame-by-frame remaster of TNG), will be more faithful. Besides that, Trek was created for TV, and still does best in that format.

So the alternate universe belongs to Paramount. CBS/Viacom owns the "real" one. At this point I sincerely hope this is the last Trek movie.

The scripts are awful, the acting below par and the cgi runs riot, destroying any chance of believability. I grew up watching Star Trek, I bought the videos and dvds from Paramount, and I was a fan. But we were all cut loose to make way for a new generation of fans, and it sticks in my craw guys and girls. There is only one Captain Kirk, one Spock, and one McCoy. And that cannot be replicated

Once was acceptable, twice was pushing it, but now the secret's out that you've given up on the show's original theme's of pioneering and exploration in favor of flashy action pieces and "witty" banter.

Star Trek meant something because, in a world of television filled with bleak futures, it was a shining beacon of hope among the stars. Now, it's just (literally, now) an outer-space re-skin of The Fast & The Furious.

I liked these actors in these roles. I thought they had promise, and I wanted to see them go on grand adventures, but this is not that. This is boring trite masquerading as a thrill ride.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
I'm a Trekkie since ST-TNG (as such, I can spout acronyms). My fave movie so far is First Contact. I measure that from the first impression I got from watching a movie, not from how well it's held up over the years.Â All this being said, Star Trek movies always suffered from the fact that they never seemed to move on from the TVshow format. JJ Abrams was right on the money, when he asked why ST movies always were shot as if they were on a tight budget and short deadline. The scope was usually as narrow as in a TV episode, and the decore was often only marginally better.Â Compare the warpcore and engineering from the pre-Abrams era to the new. Small sets, every bulkhead looked like plastic and plywood. Not exactly the feel of a huge starship the size of several city blocks. Especially later, this created a huge contrast between the interior shots and the CGI space shots. Yes, even in Nemesis. 80s, 2000s, 80s, 2000s etc
To cut it short, c'mon people! The franchise had to evolve some time! So stop complaining that the franchise isn't as stuffy as you like it.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
At least they're no longer bothering to hide the fact that have no idea what Trek is or what they're doing.  

Thank god this is the last one and the nightmare can end.  2017 can't come fast enough.  CBS will have their opportunity to prove they can do Trek better than this mess.  Here's hoping there will finally be good Star Trek airing again.  

I'm getting tired of talking to teenagers and having to explain, "No, no, see, Star Trek actually used to be deep, thoughtful, compelling storytelling.  Some of the best hours of science fiction ever televised.  The Inner Light, Measure of a Man, Best of Both Worlds, Duet, The Visitor, What You Leave Behind...  Heck, even a couple Voyager episodes were good, like Scorpion and Timeless.  Trek wasn't really about phasers and warp speed, it was about stories.  Stories about hope and courage and decency and ethics, science fiction was just the setting, they were really always about heart.  ...Hey.  Hey, stop laughing, I'm serious."

With low-brow schlock like most of Enterprise, all the TNG movies, and the Abrams movies, how can I possibly hope to explain to youngsters what Trek used to be back when it was good, before the franchise decided to let it rot on the vine?  

Help us, CBS-Kenobi.  You're our only hope.  :\

Comment: Wow you guys are pathetic. I mean seriously. If you compare every movie, or every new series that they create to the original Star Trek series then you may as well just kill the series now. It is proof in itself that the creatore of Star Trek made something special because they are still making movies about it. If every movie and every series was JUST LIKE the original then the franchise would just die, it would be boring, repeatitive, and have no life ion it what so ever. The movies are starting to move with the times, as we do. Yes there is more action in them, but that doesnt stop you feeling or connecting with the characters. It doesnt stop you from getting involved in the story. Yes maybe they could put some more memorable lines in there and maybe bring out the history a little more but they can only put so much into a movie. You guys are picking at the smallest of things, like the song choice for the trailer as an example... WTF is the point in that? Your honestly gonna sit there and bitch about a sing choice? Grow up already. Then your going to bitch about the fact that theres a motorbike in it and automatically link it to the director because he did Fast 7? again, grow up. Instead of camparing the new movies to the originbal series you need to see them as their own movie, you need to see them as the next chapater of the franchise, a franchise that is still growing, that is still gaining new fans. The new movies reach out to a new generation of fans, just like the original series did to us. I personally think its fantastic that Star Trek can go into new directions, take on new dimesions, and give new meaning to some of the most well known sci fi characters ever created. Chris Pine, Zachary Quinto, Simon Pegg, Zoe Salender and the rest of the cast are doing such an amazing job with their given charcaters and should be credited for their hard work not slated by bunch of Trekkie Fans that are clearly still stuck in the past. Get over yourselves and welcome to the new world bitches!!!!

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: Star Trek fans who hate the new movies have some valid criticisms, but the bitching and moaning about the new franchise in general is fucking pathetic. Okay, I agree that Into Darkness wasn't original, was annoying to watch, and didn't have many deep thematic elements that Star Trek usually has, but I liked the first Star Trek movie. I'm a fan of the TV shows, yet I like the new cast members because unlike most Trekkies, I accept that we are in different times. Star Trek is going to have more action because the typical philosophical material, while great, makes for a boring movie for general audiences. As sad as it is, the Star Trek fanbase isn't large enough to make for big box office numbers, and that doesn't cut it for a blockbuster film. The deeper themes can (and should) still be present, even if that means weaving a bit more action into the mix. The problem with Abrams is that while his first movie was perfect for reintroducing the characters and the franchise, basically doing the same thing for the second movie was where the criticisms that he shouldn't be handling Star Trek became valid. It's why he was perfect for directing The Force Awakens. He's good at pacing, visuals, energy, and at directing his actors, which makes him a great action movie director, but when it comes to deeper character stuff, I agree that it's better left in the hands of someone like Rian Johnson. Now, Jeremy Lin may not be that guy for this Star Trek movie, but Simon Pegg, a huge Star Trek fan, helped write the script for this movie. Everyone involved that's not Abrams (and maybe he finally knows why, too) knows that this movie needs to different. That's why, unlike the other virgin Trekkies, I'm giving this movie the chance it deserves. Good God. If you love the original shows so much, just watch them on repeat till you die and don't watch the new movies.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
I'm not really fond of this trailer; mainly because it's not giving me a story to get behind. What it's giving me is a string of action sequences held together by one-liners and explosions. 
That is not Star Trek. 
Even though Star Trek takes place in space, it is about people and what happens when these people explore the galaxy to expand their knowledge. They push the envelope and each other. They care about one another.
What we needed to see in this trailer was why and how the universe pushes back at them. Where is the conflict? Who is the enemy and where is the struggle of our heroes?
Star Trek deserves to matter. This trailer doesn't make me believe that anything matters in this film other than the next action sequence.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Trek '09 was fantastic. I have watched it a million times. It had the right amount of action for a first movie reboot.

Into Darkness was underwhelming. It's ultra liberal plot (fuck you Orci) combined with too many references to older movies/shows and messed up character development made it bad. The only good thing about it were the beautifully rendered action scenes.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
I think this movie is Beyond "mindless action".

Many of these comments are very biased towards this film and even previous films.  The first 2009 movie is a reboot that did a great job telling an original story.  Although it didn't go many places where no man has gone before it gave a sense of homage to the older series giving both the old and new trekkies/audience something to like and understand.  It's very clear that no one understood the meaning behind Into Darkness.  A sequel that focused on the Star Fleet losing their path since they were corrupted with revenge against Khan.   And Star Trek Beyond looks like they're giving what you all complained about from the last film, new worlds, new life, new adventures, etc...... So honestly what's the deal?  Is it simply because the movie is directed by Justin Lin?  Is it because you saw scenes in the trailer that had action in it?  Is that it?  It's too easy to criticize the work of a film without bothering to put yourselves in their place and see how it is like working with a production like this.  Not for just the director but for the other crew who work to make these films happen...  Not an easy job.  So far I haven't seen one legitimate reason why this film looks bad other than that it has "mindless action" and "the music doesn't fit".    Can't judge an entire movie because of one trailer.  We will have to wait and see how the film turns out when it hits theaters.

Comment:
#StandWithAxanar 

Paramount/CBS have recently decided to file a lawsuit against a fan created feature length film called Star Trek Axanar. Despite their precedent of allowing and encouraging fan works to be created, Paramount/CBS has swept in well over a year after the Axanar project was created and crowd funded to call fowl. This is unfair, untimely, and stands against the precedent these companies established in regards to fan created material.

I hope all fans of the Star Trek universe will stand against the hypocrisy of Paramount/CBS. It doesn't help that their recent efforts with this franchise have been abysmal attempts to grab more money. Now they make a tyrannical sweep against a fan film that has a truer heart of Star Trek than any recent "professional" releases. Not to mention they file this suite not during the funding campaign, nor the release of the short Prelude to Axanar, but a mere 6 months before the release of the fan film and after significant expense has been spent on the part of Axanar Productions.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
It's amazing how many people on this comments thread are forgetting that most of the 12 previous Star Trek movies are action/adventure/comedy movies FIRST, and Star Trek movies SECOND.  The very best Star Trek movies IMO are Wrath of Khan and Undiscovered Country, yet those were the two movies that pissed off Roddenberry the most!  

The movie that perhaps most resembles Roddenberry's vision was The Motion Picture, which moves at a snail's pace.  I caught it again over Christmas and the scene where Kirk and Scotty approach the Enterprise is literally 5 minutes long.  It's the exact opposite of 'entertaining.'  

What I'm saying is: this movie is no different than all the other TOS, TNG and Reboot movies.  Every fan knows that Trek lives and breathes best on TV, but let's not kid ourselves: it's ALSO a thrill to see starships on the big screen too, with a budget that can generate truly alien worlds.  

This 90 second trailer is selling the spectacle but it seems to me that the film itself will really address, for the first time in any Trek movie, the dangers of going where no one has gone before.  I can only think of the TNG episode Q Who, where the crew first encounter the Borg, that similarly highlights the very real possibility that you'll eventually bump into something you can't handle.

I'm very much looking forward to seeing a film that fulfils the promise of the 2009 movie, whilst also the new TV show in development.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
I find it interesting the use of _Sabotage_ as the trailer music. It was the same song used when Kirk, in the first of Abrams' Star Trek movies, went on a joyride in his father's old earth car. In that sequence it highlighted the theme of that scene. Cheap Fun. It felt like fan-service, and the audiences gladly ate it up... Me included. Unfortunately, Mr. Lin, that theme doesn't bode well when it is used to pitch a movie.

Do you know what this trailer makes me feel like? It makes me feel like you're milking what Abrams re-imagined. Hell, all of us assumed the fat cow you've been handed died when Abrams left..... and fuck if we weren't right. Because, from the smell of it, it seems like all you're getting out is puss. You're going to try and sell it off as the usual cream, but we *(**_or at least I_**)* are not going to buy it.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Huh.  I feel like I'm getting different things out of this trailer than everyone who sees only the action.  For me, I get three things.  One, humor - a kind of humor that I enjoy, which stems primarily from the eccentricities of the characters.  Two, the setting, which appears to be on an alien planet.  This, for me, goes back to the original movies and series quite well, and it's what I missed in the previous films.  Being stranded on an alien planet and having only their brains and their guts with them to figure out how to get off while also dealing with potentially hostile locals.  And three, a new, strong female character, of which I am always appreciative, especially in films.
I have always loved the various series and I grew up watching them, but I know I am not a real Trekkie like some, so can I ask respectfully what you guys disliked about the other new films (I read through some of the comments and saw quite a bit of hate on them)?  For me (I'm saying that a lot... haha~), I really enjoyed them.  I liked how they kept a number of the themes of the original without purely copying it and how they managed to combine action and high technology/SFX with character depth, humor, and a compelling plot/drama.  Which is all I can ask for in a good movie in general.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
First of all, a trailer is only suppose to make us aware of the movie, NOT tell us what the movie is about.  Crew in danger, Enterprise destroyed, cool.  NOT Khan returns, damages the Enterprise, finds Genesis, tries to kill Kirk, submarine battle in space, Khan is beaten, Khan tries to destroy the Enterprise with Genesis, Spock sacrifices himself to save the ship.

We've all seen Star Trek 2: The Wrath of Khan, a cinematic masterpiece that few could ever top, that we can watch over and over again knowing full damn well about the emotionalism over Spock's heroic sacrifice and solid story with solid acting.  BUT guarded by the fact that Spock is going to return on the next movie.

BUT what so few seem to realize, or even spot because the new movies were not dumb down for them, is that they doubles the humour, tripled the action, and centupled the lens flare.... yes centupled is a real word, the very thing that makes Star Trek what it is is still very much present.  The only real difference is that the story and action are streamlined without stepping on each others toes, but the purists are tripping over their own feet as they try to keep up.

Poverty, disease and war are pretty much gone on Earth in the new movies.  It's the Enterprise not on a mission to save the people from Earth from their own undoing or restoring freedom to the Federation, but the Enterprise explore us, humanity.  Seeing our successes and failures, seeing ourselves as the crew of the Enterprise.  Seeing a world not as is, but seeing it what we want it to be.  Where we come together despite our differences not because of a common enemy, but a common goal.

They define Star Trek as much as wagon trails to the stars, and they are extremely easy to spot whether you are a simple movie goer, or a hard core Trekkie like me, who has been one for nearly 40 years.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Now, this doesn't look like a bad movie. But this quick, sudden, flashy, and intense in-your-face style doesn't really seem to suit the style of Star Trek. 

Star Trek had its action, of course, but generally it was a much bolder, more dramatic, slower paced style. More based around emotion and intrigue, rather than guns blazing, jumping into a firefight and rushing headfirst into combat. This is more like the stereotypical action movie rather than the stereotypical science fiction.


Look guys, the emphasis on cheesy action is awesome and all, but save that for another movie where it would actually fit. A sci-fi with that type of style has great potential and I'd like to see it executed well, but you still want Star Trek to resemble Star Trek.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
I understand what's going on here: everyone wants the new Trek to be like the old Trek.
People, this is an alternate timeline, so there will be differences. We still don't know how many other races were affected by Nero's time-traveling shenanigans, and it might be more than we realize, which may contribute to all the action versus what we saw in the TV show.
Also, the fistfights and photon torpedoes from the TV show were probably exciting to the people way back then like this action is to us today (although taken down a few notches, I'll give you all that). And who knows? Maybe all of the action will be justified when we find out the plot, and maybe it won't. But don't forget, Pegg said that the trailer wasn't like the movie. You never know.
That said, I respect everyone's opinion. And as we all know, Star Trek has had its stupid moments. No one said that they'd be eliminated with the reboot.

But I still want to see this and don't think it looks bad.

I like the old and new Star Trek, sue me. Into Darkness actually got me to go to a movie theater, something I rarely do and even bought it on Blu-ray, Cumberbatch was tight as Khan, and the first one was sweet too and very rewatchable. Visuals do matter,  when it's actually combined with a great story, it's magic. We'll see if it sucks or not, but it's a teaser trailer, it's supposed to get your attention, especially with all the visual distractions around us these days. Comment: I'm a bit skeptical as to how this movie is going to turn out, considering how the last two Star Trek movies have shown heavy influence by Hollywood's consistent revival of old stories whilst attempting to appeal to a newer generation. The trailer seems more focused on the action and thrills, rather than the actual essence of the story but I'm not one to judge too quickly. In fact, this is only the first trailer, so I'm a bit confused as to why there is already so much hate when others haven't even seen the actual film. Don't get me wrong, based on this trailer, the movie looks like a visual masterpiece, although the common complaint here is whether or not the story will live up to the franchise's original reputation. At this point, I guess there really is only one question: Who is this film going to be for?

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Sigh, another lensflare CGI popcorn fest with no science nor intrigue to speak of.

So here`s the plot:
Ship sent to investigate some plot / rebels / others who are a threat. Ship gets whacked and destroyed. Remaining crew make allies from rebels who are against main bad aliens. yada yada pop pop lensflare lensflare.

On Science: I remember being a 4 year old kid and wondering how to make transparent aluminum. I remember being 8 and wondering how fast data could count, I remember being 13 and reading about our early attempts at bio-organic technology because of Voyager, all of my scientific interest and my knowledge of computing I owe to these years.

On morality, ethics, and shades of grey: I remembered being 15 and being horrified at what Ben Sisko did to get the Romulans into the War, I was actually, utterly, shocked.  A scifi show, teaching a 15 year old boy about the devastating and compromised nature of war and its horrors. 

As for the intrigue: I miss wondering what was past the next star, who were the next new species, what was their culture, what was their history. I miss when star trek solved technical and social problems through investigation, analysis, and judgement, and every new character they met wasn't trying to kill everything.

I mean Christ, does anyone over in Hollywood actually give a crap about the core. Have we all forgotten these words so easily?

Â Space: The final frontier.

 These are the voyages of the Starship Enterprise.

 Its ongoing mission:

 1)To explore strange new worlds

 2)To seek out new life and new civilizations

 3)To boldly go where no one has gone before.


Today it may as well be "to boldy go somewhere relatively local and kick ass"

I miss Star Trek : (

Comment: I'm probably going to regret putting this here on account of my inbox getting spammed, but here goes: to those who want to see the action parts of this, I applaud you. The same goes for all those who want there to be mainly intellectual material. In the end, though, can we take a moment to just stop arguing about how this looks like Fast and Furious in space or that they're happy that the old show is dead? Llet's all have respect for one another and move on. This is just a movie. Now before the hate starts, let me remind you that this is just a trailer. We have yet to see the full works. Maybe it has the right amount of both- which could very well happen as we have a new director. Maybe it won't. At the very least, let's wait until the movie comes out. And to those who's at that the trailers are there to spark discussion and that we didn't see anything but action and therefor there will be no intellect in this movie- would you put just talking in a trailer to draw people in to see a movie, or would you put the impactful material? I'll leave that to you. I bid you a due.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
On some level, I appreciate that Star Trek is still going and people are still watching it. 
But this trailer concerns me. I do not want Star Trek and its subsequent adaptations to become nothing more than Fast and Furious in Space. Of course some will say that JJ Abrams Star Treks were just that, but those have some emotional and philosophical complexity if you look closely, and they exemplify Kirk and Spock's brotherhood.  
I want to like this movie, but the trailer looks bad. Beastie Boys was a poor choice of music and it completely disregards the last part of Star Trek Into Darkness. What happened? Did they start their journey and get recalled or some BS? I realize the movie format is not as great as TV for the Exploration theme, but they could at least try something different than "enterprise/earth in danger, must battle evil villain and nearly or completely destroy the Enterprise."
All in all, I hope the movie proves me wrong, but this was a poor start for a movie that already has an army of detractors at its back.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: Beast Wars!! I mean... Star Trek! I remember the first official trailer for star trek 2009 was pretty much on this level of action movie tone and people were freaked out, then they released trailer 3? I think, which had a much more dramatic and serious and EPIC tone, which made people a lot happier. I really really don't think beastie boys was a good decision for a star trek trailer. It makes this movie look insecure about itself when it relies so heavily on referencing such a small aspect of a previous installment in order to boost it's appeal and marketability in such a generic way. They have a real opportunity to distance this installment from Abrams obvious Star Wars fetish he just couldn't resist shoving into the last two movies throughout, and I hope they take it in a direction Abrams couldn't or wouldn't, and embrace the plethora of content and ideas Trek has offered over the years and what made it special to begin with. Here I see the potential for a story about human ingenuity in a desperate situation, which, yeah, can be a platform for an interesting story if told right, just as many episodes of trek have done before in a similar way. The creators of this are clearly caught between capturing what made the abrams treks appealing, and what makes ALL the rest of Trek appealing, while telling a story the previous films didn't (presumably). not an easy spot to be in. I will say that Abrams had some really great ideas for the cinematography and ways the camera moved and flowed and framed shots,more so in the first movie especially. And overall I don't feel that I am seeing the same level of competence and artistry here in that regard. I have to be completely honest and just say too, this movie looks cheaper than the last two, way cheaper. From Chris Pines hair and makeup to the seemingly limited locations and overall toned down use of special effects and apparent lack of truly epic set pieces seen in previous films ( with the exception of whatever happens to the enterprise that shit looks serious), I'm definitely not getting the same vibe here that made the Abrams Treks appealing in their own right in terms of the epic scale and adventure. I just have to wait and see like everyone else, but I am sorta not thrilled about this so far.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
oh wow. A female character who's an expert in hand to hand combat and has an accent..... never seen that shit before. Hear me out for a second everyone.
Can we diversify the female roles in action movies just a tiny bit? its like the writers copied and pasted Michonne from the walking dead, then changed her outfit to avoid a lawsuit. And theres about a dozen others exactly like her. Get past the idea that a girl in a movie has to be either a hyper feminine love interest for one of the main characters, or a hyper masculine badass who still contributes almost nothing, and accept that you could just make them a regular damn character. Think if captain pike did everything he did in the first two movies, but was played by a girl. the movie would be NO DIFFERENT except that it would add variety to the classic "mentor turned parental-figure helps out his favorite student" shtick. I mean its not like kirk was introduced playing death metal in his bedroom, reading a copy of playboy magazine and wearing the equipment from 3 different sports at once, all while watching Black Hawk Down, because his gender isn't a focus of his character. his character focuses on his goofiness, strong sense of honor, friendship with spock, and ability to rise to any occasion. So if the main character can slide by without the movie throwing in our faces that he's a guy, why can't the same thing happen with the token female character
make it happen hollywood, it'll be awesome

Comment:
Oh wait. I've seen this before. Remember when they announced Daniel Craig as the new James Bond and the entire world turned on him thinking he was ill-suited to play a legendary character? There were new websites, polls and entire blogs dedicated requesting his removal from the film. Only to see that Casino Royale was a kick ass movie!

Oh and when Heath Ledger was announced as the Joker and world bemoaned Christiphoer's choice. How dare he cast a pretty blonde boy who has only had a handful of small films, in this iconic role. And then first trailer came out with some shots of the joker and we couldn't wait to see WTF Heath had done with this character. He looked amazingly sinister and fit for the role. And then the movie came out and the world crowned him the best Joker ever.

Well I may be proven wrong, but I won't judge Lin till I have seen the movie for myself. After a too few incidents of been proven wrong I now reserve judgement till after the fact. I think you should too.

OK so I am a fan since TOS ( yes I'm old). Back in the day I got attitude and refused to watch TNG from the start bcs it wasn't TOS. Then I watched and got totally hooked. When I thought about it, I kind of  realized I was going against everything Gene stood for. He wanted to challenge the world to allow things to evolve. Every series has had detractors and purists who rage against it and I can respect their love and defence but for ME I realized I was being foolishly unsupportive of exactly what Papa Gene was all about if I didn't give them a chance. Remember Elvis was the devil to one generation's parents and now he's considered tame as all hell.

Comment: My ideal Star Trek movie plot:  The enterprise is traveling with a eccentric, genius scientist on board, there are rumors about him not being completely sane, but Star Fleet has allowed him to get samples from a rarely visited, distant planet.  The second in command, and has two sex androids whom he calls friends, but because their brains were differently than a positronic one, and its hard to tell if the robots have free will or not, he has legal ownership over them, causing division among the crew.  After being forced to place stricter limitations on using the holodeck, the captain is working with available counselors to stop "portable holodeck" addiction among members of the crew, with failed success; there are posters on the wall urging people to seek help; people are becoming disenchanted with some of the decisions of those in charge and a few aren't showing up to their posts.  A stranded vessel gets picked up who are travelling merchants who seem both rich and seedy, and refuse to discuss what their cargo is, causing it to go on lockdown.  The captain agrees to take them back to their home since its on the way, but its later found out that they are illegal weapon dealers and the enterprise is taking them to their customers.  The old scientist is reclusive and has been seen dragging a tall crate into the holodeck every night, what nobody knows is that the crate contains a child borg, and the samples he is actually trying to obtain are not from a planet.

Comment: Why so much hate. You cannot do the kinds of stories on the big screen that you can on TV. To justify the cost movie companies want big movies. It's funny, after the 2009 movie came out people online were screaming for the villain of the next movie to be Kahn. The writers listened and then those very people reversed course and HATED IT! Now a trailer comes out for the next movie and suddenly everyone seems to be able to tell if it's good or bad from a few minute commercial for the the flick. Star Trek like Bond will live on even if the original actors, writer and producers aren't involved anymore, and to try to keep new people coming in they will change the course of Star Trek. Paramount used to scrimp on ST's budget, now they throw nearly 200 million at the screen and they expect some return, so instead of bitching about how much you hate, be thankful you still can go to a theater and see it every few years. Even if it isn't to your liking, at least it's still there.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: You need really deft hands to make Star Trek films carry the philosophical weight found in the TV series. On the big screen, you are going to need to have heavy, gritty action and drama to satisfy today's attention spans. However, the Martian was quite capable of doing just that. Star Trek is very beloved because of its philosophical and exploratory nature. The reason I have had a problem with JJ is that he doesn't care about Star Trek and has a profound disconnect with it. He made action films and tried to piece together relationships in a flimsy manner. The writers he chose were not any better. The two movies come off as soulless and hackneyed scripted action films. There isn't anything that makes me  really enjoy and love these characters as I have from the TV Series.  Star Trek films have never been completely strong. The later TNG movies after First Contact were abominable. I didn't even like Enterprise the TV series at first but then when I did a front to back watching of Trek I fell in love with it. If you wanted gritty action with many philosophical underpinnings - you had it in that show. Star Trek is a beautiful world of very thoughtful characters and political, philosophical and humanistic proportions. It's why I feel so strongly about it and it's preservation. It isn't mere nostalgia. I am a kid of the late 70s. I grew up with TNG. I saw TOS later. I don't respect JJ for what he has done to Star Trek.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: I see a lot of people complaining that this appears to be an action movie, not a "Star Trek" movie which should be more "cerebral." Who says an action movie can't be cerebral? I like this trailer because it doesn't give away any of the plot. If you had a trailer that was promoting the more cerebral aspect of the film then it would have to give away big chunks of the plot and will likely alienate a large portion of viewers (remember this is a summer blockbuster intended to make money). A cerebral action movie is the pop-culuter equivalent of a philosophical thought experiment. Consider the classic though experiment, a train is about to hit and kill 12 people, you have the power to divert the train to a different track that will only kill 1 person. Do you divert the train and actively kill or do nothing and allow 12 people to die? Imagine if they made that into a movie, it would be action packed and cerebral at the same time.

Comment: Guess this is what happens when you lose J.J. Abrams as Director. Well, in not to long we'll know if the price was worth it. If STAR WARS The Force Awakens is as good as i hope it is then yeah throwing STAR TREK is worth it any day. But if The Force Awakens is a epic fail... Well then i'm going to be pretty darn pissed. And i'll get pissed at STAR TREK and hate on it because no matter what happens i'm a STAR WARS fanboy and therefor can't let myself hate on it no matter what they do wrong. Prais Jar Jar!!!! But for reals tough... This trailer wasn't any good. I mean like what the fuck happened? STAR TREK was actually pretty darn good! And INTO DARKNESS just blew me away! Having never really liked STAR TREK that's saying alot! Both the past films where great. But this doesn't seem great. They lose the ship.... That's one BIG fail. The style of the film is... Well it isn't really good in my opinion. Where are the lense flairs? And what the heck is the plot of this film? A albino fights them and then they join forces against Dr. Evilfish and win using the Bike of Awesomeness? Sorry... I'm not going to judge the film based on the trailer. But the trailer dosn't make it look any good. This just looks sad. The very first trailer doesn't have to be the best trailer. But if it fails to give a good impression then that's a flop... The first trailer has the most riding on it. This one failed in my eyes. Let's hope it's just a bad trailer and the movies isn't as bad.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Okay kids, settle down and let me explain why J.J. Abrams is a genius.
Star Trek, while being the hyper-generic "Dungeons and Dragons" of science fiction, was always made exclusively for this super-niche audience. Star Trek was made by talented artists and intelligent nerds, and that's wonderful. Kudos. However, it always lacked 1 thing: A director who just wanted to make a good movie. THAT is what Star Trek has always lacked. The best Star Trek movies were always ones where the director decided to do something different and add a little flavor that wasn't there before. Star Trek is bland. Let's face it. And let me explain what I mean.
I loved Prometheus. Dense, complex and deep writing don't bother me. I loved 2001: Space Oddessy. Really slow pacing to set the tone doesn't bother me. What I don't like about Star Trek is that it's always been very bland. No personality. It was so generic, yet so inexpressive that each episode/movie just felt like a generic smoothie of science fictiony/Star Trekky stuff.
This fundamental flaw is the very thing that J.J. Abrams immediately keyed in on and corrected. Yes his films have various internal flaws, but no script is truly perfect. 
Just take this for what it is and try to enjoy it. J.J. hasn't let us down yet, let's just go with it and try to have some fun for the first time in 50 years.

Comment:
Summary of the comments:

Fans: I want more of the same old shit that made for a dichotomy of terrible and good movies flip flopping like crazy and episodes that make less then no sense.

Movie Makers: Sure, here's a new spin on the Kirk origin story keeping most of the details fairly correct.

Fans: ARGH! THIS IS TERRIBLE!

Movie Makers: Ok, here's a sequel which pays homage to the movie you morons claim is the best, Wrath of Khan.

Fans: ARGH! THIS IS TERRIBLE.

Movie Makers: FINE FUCK IT! Here's a completely new movie that has nothing to do with the original series or movies at all except for the crew and the ship. And we're going to destroy the ship so you can't piss and moan about that anymore. In fact, we're going to make this movie so hard core about the people that we're going to introduce a warring faction of natives to this new world with the Enterprise being caught between, and likely needing to help settle the conflict, that in effect we're going back to TNG style Star Trek (the best Star Trek).

Fans: ARGH! THIS IS TERRIBLE.


Seriously. Listen to yourselves. You are just the worst kinds of fans. You're asking for movies that are exactly like the originals. News flash: The original movies all sucked. ALL of them. It wasn't until TNG that any Star Trek movie wasn't a complete ball of pure garbage.

And that's largely in part to the fact that Kirk is just straight up the worst Captain ever. He's basically James Bond in space. Which is terrible.

Comment: I'm a fan of Star Trek and Star Wars more so on the Star Wars front (better marketing, toys, games, etc). I've seen ever single Star Trek/Wars related film, T.V episode, series, books etc... There is very little I don't know about in either of these incredible universes. What I can tell you is this; some movies will be better than others based on the methodology to reach different people covering different opinions and views. Not every movie made by either franchise can win all people's hearts and vote. What I do know is this, each time another movie is made, more and more people are aware of these universes hence more money for the creators and franchises. These movies provide jobs and entertainment = plain and simple.  I for one couldn't care or less for this trailer as compared to the Force Awakens trailer - two completely different levels of WOW factor for me personally. At the end of day, die hard fans will pick apart everything they want and they have every right too as they are fans. At the beginning of the next day, who gives a shit. By the way, I hope more and more films are made, it will help everyone with the Event. Cheers.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Long time hardcore *Star Trek* fan here. I like to believe that I am objective enough to be able to see things (films especially) from different perspectives. And, although I do find that these new films aren't "ye old Trek," they still do offer some decent entertainment. Whereas the old shows delved deep into thought-provoking topics/themes, these new films just graze the surface while being injected with plenty of spectacle as substitution. And, from this trailer anyhow, this one does not seem to be slowing down in that trend. So, we'll have to wait and see just how much the "surface to substance" ratio has been affected before I decide on how I will feel about the new films going forward.

Are the new films bad? No, they aren't. They are entertaining. Are they as good as (or better than) ANYTHING Trek that has come previously? Definitely not. However, they are still good enough to watch and enjoy.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
The first line of the opening crawl is "Luke Skywalker has disappeared."
 
The first sentence in the movie is "This will begin to make things right", said by Max von Sydow. Poe Dameron came to him to get the map to Luke Skywalker for The Resistance.
 
Max von Sydow's role is just a cameo, he has about 10 sentences before Kylo Ren kills him.
 
The Empire is now The First Order, The Rebels are now The Resistance, more extreme fraction of the New Republic, who are supposedly pussies. We only see the New Republic planet for a few seconds before it's destroyed by the Starkiller base.
 
Almost no one in the movie believes that Jedis and Luke Skywalker ever existed.
 
Kylo Ren captures Poe and uses the Force to stop laser blast so that it remains floating in the air, frozen in place.
 
Finn helps captured Poe to escape from the Star Destroyer only because he cannot pilot TIE fighter himself. Poe is an expert pilot, Finn can shoot lasers. They become friends.
 
Finn's "real name" is FN and four numbers. Poe starts to call him "Finn" because it's easier to pronounce. FN likes it.
 
After 20 minutes, we are supposed to think that Poe Dameron was killed in the TIE crash on Jakku. He reappers near the end (he ejected before the crash) to lead the attack on Starkiller base. He is not in the film very much. Finn wears Poe's jacket during most of the movie.
 
Rey meets Finn, they steal the Millennium Falcon from the junkyard and fly away. Han and Chewie catch them soon, followed by two groups of racially-stereotyped space gangsters.
 
Chewbacca is wounded by space gangsters soon after he appears and spends most of the remaining time doing nothing. Rey takes his place as Falcon's pilot, proving herself to Han.
 
Kylo Ren is Han and Leia's son. He is "Master of The Knights of Ren" but it's not explained what it means.
 
Kylo Ren's real name is Ben. He was trained by Luke but then turned to the Dark Side which was the reason for Luke blaming himself and disappearing.
 
The Starkiller base charges by draining suns and then destroys whole solar systems. The shot in trailer with Kylo Ren and red flare is the Starkiller base firing. Guess what, the Starkiller base can be destroyed by flying in her trench and shooting the "oscillator" or whatever.
 
Han meets Kylo at the Starkiller base/planet and tries to persuade him to return with him. "I am torn apart, father. But I know what I must do. Can you help me?" - "Of course, my son." They almost embrace. Kylo pierces Han with lightsaber. "Thank you, father." Dead Han falls into the shaft on the Starkiller base. Yes, he is dead. Most definitely.
 
Leader Snoke is the bald CGI bad guy with large scar across his face. He has snake-like movements but his body is never clearly seen. His motivation or origin is never explained. He gives orders to Kylo Ren and General Hux (who hate each other). Most of the characters don't know about Snoke's existence.
 
General Hux has screaming monologue in front of thousands of Stormtroopers: "We stand upon this mighty weapon you've built. Everyone will bow to The First Order. Today will be remembered as the last day of The Republic!" Afterwards, all Stormtroopers raise their fists. Very nice Der Fuhrer moment.
 
Fan service: Holochess. The levitating training ball from Episode 4. Admiral Ackbar. Rey living in the AT-AT wreckage. "1138" mentioned. Garbage chute and trash compactor mentioned. Kesel Run mentioned.
 
Simon Pegg plays an alien called Ankar Plutt who took care of Rey when she was very little and her parents disappeared. Now he runs a junkyard on Jakku and buys scrap from Rey. His face and voice is not recognizable.
 
Apart from Han and Chewie, all the "original characters" (Leia, R2D2, C3PO) only appear after two thirds of the movie, when The Resistance lands on Maz Kanata's planet.
 
Maz Kanata (small CGI gypsy) is the new Yoda and explains everything cryptically. Nobody understands her.
 
Han and Leia see each other for the first time after many, many years and have a touching conversation about their son: "You can still save him." / "How can I save him when Luke couldn't?" / "Luke was a Jedi, your are his father."
 
Kylo Ren and Rey have duel of wills. Rey wins, telling Kylo: "I sense your fear. You are afraid that you will never be as strong as Darth Vader."
 
Kylo Ren talks to Vader's helmet: "Show me the darkness. I will finish what you started, grandfather."
 
R2D2 spends the whole movie powered down and doesn't do anything until 5 minutes at the very end when it's discovered that crucial part of the Skywalker map is in his memory, probably but there by Luke long time ago. (It's not very clear but Luke appears with R2D2 in a flashback.)
 
Rey has a weird dream/flashback after she finds Luke's lightsaber in Maz Kanata's castle and touches it. The dream contains lots of quick imagery and short voiceovers by Yoda and Obi-Wan. Several famous shots in trailers (Kylo and his posse, Luke's mechanical arm on R2D2) are from this dream montage and are never explained in the movie.
 
Finn's origin (his skin color, who are his parents, why he hates the First Order) is never explained.
 
C3PO's red hand is never explained. In fact, there are many things that are never explained in this movie...
 
Both Finn and Rey have lightsaber duel with Kylo in the forest on the Starkiller planet/base. Finn is badly wounded and spends rest of the movie in a coma. Rey finally falls in love with him. (He loved her from the first sight.)
 
Starkiller base/planet is succesfully destroyed by The Resistance. We don't know what happens with Kylo Ren (who was there) but he probably survived. Snoke sends the message to Hux to "Bring Kylo Ren to me complete his training."
 
The last sentence of the movie is "May the Force be with you", said by Leia to Rey.
 
After the last sentence, there is an extended sequence without dialogue: Rey leaves the Resistance base in the Millennium Falcon with Chewbacca. They find remote planet where Luke is hiding (because they now have the map), Rey goes to the "first Jedi Temple" (which looks like ruins of some Scottish castle on a rocky island). Luke is there, dressed in old Obi-Wan style hood. Rey returns his sword to him. Apart from this sequence, Luke only appears for three seconds in Rey's previous flashback. Luke speaks no words in the whole movie and is onscreen maybe for 30 seconds total. He never meets anyone else than Rey.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Star Trek III: Beyond Ridiculous.
Trek fans are used to being punched in the face but this seems a bit more below the belt. 

The only reason star trek has survived 5 decades is because of the fans, and how do you reward millions of fans who have supported Star Trek for 50 years?
Take everything about it that they love out, or (to paraphrase Simon Pegg) "make it less Star Trek-y".

This wont be a Star Trek Movie. This will be a Guardians of the Fast and Furious Movie staring the characters of Star Trek.

Paramount are trying to appeal to a different audience by (pardon the pun) alienating the audience they already have. The greatest asset with Star Trek fans is they are fiercely loyal, and have stuck with the franchise for generations (that one was intentional). They host podcasts, dress up as characters, have heated debates about canon and the next generation (ok, ill stop now) of star trek fans will do the same. 

This different audience that paramount are trying to appeal to are fickle, short attention span types who tend to forget about something the moment something newer and shinier comes out. These people wont stick with Star Trek for another 50 years even if they do enjoy it, and lets be honest, the fast and furious types are not exactly famed for their enjoyment of all things Trekkie.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
I enjoy these movies.  I'm excited to see this.  But not for a second do I actually think "Star Trek" when I watch them.  This is "Abrams Trek".  Abrams is perfectly suited to Star Wars, I'm glad he switched to that for sure, but I encourage you to do what I do: Don't think of this as Star Trek.

The new films are great on their own.  Good story telling, great action, great effects, good humour, just all-round good films.  But every last real Trek fan is either content with the original series, or wants a new Prime universe TV Show.  With about 25% (give or take 10%) of fans still waiting for a redo for the end of Enterprise plus a film.  And a film for the Voyager crew.  ...and something DS9-related.  I honestly don't know how Trek wasn't profitable enough to keep that train going.

All of this in my opinion, with zero fact checking.  Obviously.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Trekkie opinion.

Ok, yes...this makes me angry, but first let me say this. The 2009 Trek was good and I quite enjoyed it. Why? Because whomever was heading it up was aware of the rampant fans if they messed it up. So they made a plot point that would satisfy us. Aka...and alternate universe. They took great care in casting and even did some wonderful nods to TOS.

That being said...what in the heck makes them think that this is Star Trek?????

Star Trek is so much more than an action-packed flick (or at least that's how it was created it be!)

If you are truly interested in the heart of Star Trek watch these episodes of the various series and skip this wannabe movie. Really disappointed with what I just saw!

The Original Series: "Let that be your last battlefield"

The Next Generation: "The measure of a man"

Deep Space Nine: "Past tense" parts 1 & 2

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: urgh. *Puke* A fast paced, unintelligent throw up ride with tons of CGI and cliches as characters. It's like throwing a bucket of acrylic paint at the Mona Lisa and calling it art. Just another action flick with Trek jargon used to sell tickets. This is what you get when the marketing team orders and writes the script. When I look at the last two movies and now this one, I  just feel like Star Trek has been cheapened and dumbed down. Gone are the days where Star Trek was intelligent, thought provoking, ahead of its time. This is not the Star Trek of The Next generation, Deep Space 9 and Voyager  know. It is a caricature of Star Trek where flashy scenes. camera glares and sexy, good looking individuals get to be flashy and sexy and make bold choices and throw around trek jargon every 2 seconds to remind us that this is, in fact, a Star Trek production,  but it's not just like any Star Trek - this is a hip Star Trek. Clearly this segment was made to appeal to the Justin Bieber generation and in that regard I am sure it will be a box office hit.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
STiD wasn't about much. Is this about ANYTHING? This is possibly the most incoherent generic action flick trailer I've seen in several years.

Thus far not one of the NuTrek films has ascended to the level of being basic science fiction, let alone anything that bears any resemblance to Star Trek. That's fine, painting a name on a generic set of cheap explosions to sell tickets to 8 year olds everywhere. If there's a market for it, then have at it. What I can't figure out is why anyone with a triple digit IQ would actually pay a movie ticket for something with such a total lack of anything novel, whatsoever. I already have generic action flicks at home.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: I think Star Trek has needed to cowboy up for some time. The best parts of Star Trek TNG were always the high action episodes where the Federation got together and tried to crush the Borg. I know a lot of people enjoyed the high brow attitude which Star Trek has developed but I just can't help loving this new focus on action. The best part of Star Trek: Into Darkness for me was the last 20 minutes when the Enterprise got blasted into swiss cheese, Spock wrecks Kahn on the back of a speeding hovercraft, and Kirk takes one for the team. Scottie and Bones were hilarious throughout. If I'm ever feeling the need to watch a bunch of stuffed shirts bumble through life while helplessly struggling against their personal demons I'd just spend more time at my job. The more humor and adventure the better in my opinion.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
I can see why people hate the trailer; as it only showcases action, snappy one liners and rock music without teasing any kind of story line. But the actual clips are not that different from scenes in the last 2 movies. They had similar jokes and an abundance of explosions and fight scenes. Seems like more of the same to me. Bang average, albeit enjoyable, space action films. 

The JJ Abrams films were nothing like the old Trek films to begin with, so raging over this one a bit silly. I expect there will be the same drama, villainy and story as the in the last two films. The Fast&Furious director probably didn't write the script here. But I guess he might have had a hand in putting together this trailer.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
I hope the people who cut this trailer (and chose Sabotage as the soundtrack) are fired immediately.  This trailer is a poor follow up to yesterday's explosive Independence Day trailer that is getting people excited and hyped for the sequel (which is quite a feat since virtually no one asked for a sequel to begin with), unlike this trailer that has left people dumbfounded and uninterested.  Honestly, I have zero interest in seeing this film because I absolutely hate this trailer.  Motocross jumps, karate kicks, over the top stunts (especially from Scotty, of all characters), Jesus Christ...what happened to this franchise?!

Here's the thing, I'm not against action and adventure in a Star Trek film, it can be done!  Look at Star Trek: First Contact; this film pulls off being an excellent sci-fi action film without losing touch with the Star Trek franchise.  Star Trek Beyond, from what I've read in the trade press, and from what I've seen in this trailer, is nothing more than another dumb action movie that's part of the Star Trek brand in name only.

Paramount wanted a less "Star Trek-ey" film from the writers this time around....and by all means, they got it.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: Historically, Star Trek films have done hardly any business overseas and the international market is where the biggest profits come from in today's motion picture rat race. Overseas markets do not want Star Trek: TMP, they want Star Trek: Fast and Furious. In order for Paramount to make big $$$ Star Trek MUST appeal to the overseas audiences. There are simply not enough Trekkie fan-boys and die-hards on earth to make the kind of money Paramount is looking for. Hollywood, in general, is making movies for a global market, not a limited crowd of Americans. In effect, all the negative comments being made about this trailer -- here and on other sites -- is going into one Paramount ear and out the other.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: I'll say it, a disappointing trailer. Too comical, have no clue what the plot is (not saying it should give it away, but we have like no clue what on earth is going on),  not even a hint on what the villain is going to be like, and the trailer has nothing distinctive about it whatsoever, just a mash of random action explosions and whatnot. No suspense either, just immediately introduces us to the Star Trek characters and next thing you know, a bunch of random explosion crap things happening. In terms of direction, this movie looks well directed and will probably have some pretty sweet action sequences, but the movie's tone and writing look AWFUL. Just hope the movie is better than this trailer. I'm not even too familiar with Star Trek, but I can tell, this isn't Star Trek, it feels much more like a Guardians of the Galaxy wannabe.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Was there any thought given to concept, narrative or character development?
Do they even bother with screenplay writers any more?
Or is the goal simply a montage of fun, visual moments and cute lines.
Producers, you can still have subtlety, depth & nuanced ideas, characters & genuine emotions with sci-fi action.
But let's not bother, let's make a dumbed-down bromance buddy action flick.
I'm surprised Channing Tatum and Jonah Hill aren't in it.
I predict fun, meaningless action with numerous plot errors & character inconsistencies. And hot chicks!
But we'll include the manufactured emotion of a quiet, "serious" scene (with sombre music).
For Star Trek fans, I guess it's true: In space no one can hear you scream.

Still, just my opinion.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Ok, movie trailer editor guy-  basic lesson in film tone:  The score over the imagery will always have a dramatic impact on the way something is perceived.  

You want to attract people with an intriguing mystery? Leave the score silent and dub some eerie dialogue from the movie over your cuts.  

You want to convey a "this might be the END" vibe?  Stick with low tones, sweeping cello and bass, or go the Inception route and do the plunging BWAAAAAAA's over epic wide angle shots.  

You want to show that your movie is just a mindless action romp they won't remember the next day?  That's when you slap 8,000 action shots together in quick succession and dub over everything with an extraordinarily cliche pop song.

This is basic shit, guy.  So I have to assume you put this laughable "teaser" together in this way because there wasn't enough substance in the film to convey any other tone.  If I'm wrong, prove it Paramount.

Comment: and the dumb down of the franchise continues..Gene Rodenbbery's orginal vision of the Star Trek universe was one of optimism, of cooperation, and cerebral content that asked the big questions. Action and gratuitous violence was always secondary to a good plot and intelligent character development. This started in TOS and continued with TNG, DS9, and even Voyager...Then Paramount decided to hire new script writers with the intent of capturing the 12-24 demographic...and we are left with a shell of how cutting edge, controversial and cerebral the original franchise was. Ironically there are many more people that are Trek fans that are NOT in that "magic" demographic..and if the braintrust at Paramount would understand that, well they might instead make a movie that surpasses, dare I say it, the popularity of Star Wars...
