Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
For all the haters who've never really grasped what the creators of the tv series ever tried to do... yes, Star Trek isn't originally heavy on epic action-ness... but you have to wonder if the only reason that was the case was because it was the 60s and they just weren't able to pull off scenes like in these new movies. Technological resources for big budget action were very scarce, and it's even been openly admitted that a lot of the tv show (especially the first have of season 1) was met with a lot of close calls deadline-wise (i.e. The Menagerie parts 1 and 2 being the saving grace period that allowed them to catch up with the project, look it up). I wouldn't be entirely convinced if someone tried to tell me that Gene Roddenberry would be terribly opposed to having JJ Abrams and/or Justin Lin.

Just sayin'.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: You know, I've made this argument a million times and I've made this argument since the first reboot movie. The original Star Trek films are old and slow, sure, us old school Star Trek fans love those shows and SOME of those movies, but take off your rose-tinted nostalgia glasses for one fucking second and think; think for one goddamn second that an old style Star Trek movie would alienate a ton of viewers that want a fun summer action movie. They don't want to bring in entirely old audiences, they want new people to start loving the series as well, so why can't you be fucking happy that this series is acting as a gateway for new fans? But you know what? If you want Star Trek to die by confusing new fans with a slow ass pace and a boring movie, you go right ahead but me, personally, I want Star Trek to live on and get more and more popular. So if you don't like the new Star Trek, shut the fuck up and go watch TNG for the billion and first time. (And Sabotage was in the first Star Trek reboot so stop bitching)

The swarm-like attacks could indicate some kind of Insectoid Xindi tactic. Didn't see any Aquatics or Aerials.

Almost certainly a Xindi storyline. It looks like maybe in this timeline there is some kind of Xindi Civil War? Perhaps the Reptilians (and maybe Insectoids) are now attacking Earth, after subjugating the other Xindi species.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
To anyone saying "It's trying to be fresh and inclusive for the younger audiences, and make a profit":

Take a look at Star Trek: First Contact.

First Contact had action. Five minutes in, and we're already seeing a Borg Cube taking out ships by the second. Then we see a bombing, a firefight, a fight aboard a starship, another firefight, etc. We even see Picard with a goddamn tommy gun.

But the thing was, First Contact also had a story, and nuanced messages. We got two new, dynamic characters introduced, we got backstory for the world we know and love, we learned old flaws of our favorite characters, and we felt for them. They did action, they did science, they did drama, and *NONE OF IT WAS BORING*. It was a smart movie, but like this, it was accessible to everyone as long as they knew the characters.

Everyone loved it. It's still the 4th-highest-grossing Trek movie yet, including the reboots, and it almost made double its budget. The film buffs enjoyed the direction and themes, the mass audience ate up the action, and the nerds had all the technobabble and continuity they could want.

It's too early to judge Beyond, but it just seems generic and dumbed-down, even for the reboot. The trailer has a couple cool shots, and the bit with Bones is pretty funny, but that's all I'm seeing. I'm not mad about it, but I'm getting tired of what we're getting, and I think the audiences are too.

Comment:
Ugh.. whoever designed this trailer, does not understand Star Trek.  That said, after watching a few times to really absorb the content.  Minus horribly picked music.  This does look closer to TOS Trek.  You have the crew on a planet, dealing with a predicament.  People are saying something about Guardians, over the alien girl?  There was also an alien girl in old trek.  Almost every time, and Kirk was always the one romancing her with a few small exceptions.  Except in this day and age, the girl is not just there to be a pretty face.  She actually does things relevant to the plot.  

I've actually got some hope for this.  The last two were not that bad either, but certainly the feel is different.  This will be closer.. give it a chance guys.  And try to ignore that stupid trailer.  It's clearly designed to market to the younger, short attention span and blow everything up crowd.  Maybe even turn the sound off entirely so you can just absorb what's actually happening in the shots.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Every line in this trailer seems to be either a platitude or a quippy one-liner followed by an explosion, and it's giving me second-hand embarrassment.  This one, like its two predecessors, seems to be another punishment of Ex$plo$ive Blockbu$ter $chlock.  Star Trek used to be defined by its interest in social reform, non-violent problem solving, and publicly approachable philosophy.  

The Original Series had the first ever nationally televised interracial kiss, TNG challenged gender norms by having men wear mini dresses and by writing episodes with obvious LGBT parallels, Voyager made a point to include a richly diverse cast and a female captain, DS9 had a black commander, a gender fluid main character, and often wrote episodes that explored the devastation and aftermath of war.  

Meanwhile, the new movies have a whopping total of two people of color in the main cast, a white-washed Kahn, three total named female characters who have lines (all of whom have appeared partially naked).   Zero gay couples, zero trans people, zero disabled characters, and a huge emphasis on violent "problem solving". I can't believe it's 2015 and this huge budget series is ethically straggling behind a schmaltzy TV show written in the 60s.

Star Trek is supposed to be political and intelligent, so if you don't want to make a Star Trek movie, then stop pretending to make them.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: This  is it.  Star Trek fans need to unite and do something.  The "don't watch it" is the only weapon left in the Trek fandom to stop these embarrassments. They harm the franchise by reducing the value and message of what Star Trek is to a younger audience.  I know from the conventions Star Trek fans are upset about the current films. There are not enough "young new" fans to bring in the money Paramount expects or needs to keep making these movies; the success of these movies still depends upon the long term Star Trek loyalists. The last movie barely broke even for what the studio spent. I know the feeling of obligation, we Star Trek fans feel, to to see everything Trek. But, at a minimum, stay away for the first two weeks of release. This is the period the studio makes the most money, without sharing with the theaters. That is enough to send a true message and stop production of these special effect extravaganza, no substance, shadows of Star Trek.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: Feelings for this trailer. . . well they're finally off planet. That's a plus, but it doesn't have a star trek feel. The first two movie trailers weren't action packed and it still held a certain, awe to it. This trailer, with the music choice (which might be why I feel this way), kind of makes me feel like I should put on some leather, grab a couple guns and get ready to kick some a$$. Not something I should feel when watching Star Trek. Especially since I avoid action movies due to the redundancy (unless it's marvel). I will reserve final judgment. There's a lot of trailers that show all the actiony parts in the trailer and the rest of the movie doesn't have that. So it's possible that this is one of those times. Also with lowered expectations, I might enjoy it more. But I went into Darkness (I know a lot of people hated that one) with high expectations,Â and I loved it so much, I got into TOS.Â  Til now I held the reboot and TOS separateÂ  in my likes. The main reason being that the reboot had yet to go on the five year mission and doing its own thing. This is changing that. Lets pray, they don't screw it up.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
I'm surprised that the movie will probably be, or at least looks, more "intimate." That is a positive. I don't have a problem with a action, however this doesn't even feel like Star Trek. I'm just hoping the silly marketing is covering up something special.

My biggest problem is that after two films I still don't give a crap about the characters. Why would i care about them doing anything now? This is why star trek died more than a decade ago, the characters became secondary to the plot. The bad thing is that this film might be great and no one will see it because in the last film Spock of all people decided to punch his emotions out.

Star Trek is a great franchise that i love, but it doesn't have the strength of Star Wars, nor its blind fan,s to endure complete madness and survive. Of course the first Avengers trailer was terrible too and the second made it amazing. We will see.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
It does finally seem at least less villain-focused than the past three films. It looks a bit more like it's shooting for something along the lines of Insurrection or Star Trek V, in that we do get to see an alien civilization and some kind of revolt perhaps, though hopefully better executed than in those films. It looks lighter and a bit more problem-solving than villain-killing, so it looks promising. I'm cautiously optimistic that this might finally feel a bit more like TV Trek, but with movie Trek action and over-sized emotion.

I noticed Orci, McKay, and Payne are still listed as writers.  Perhaps there influence is still there, including Orci's wish that the film move away from villains.

I hope Elba's playing more of an antagonist that meets Kirk halfway, and it ends in a truce with both sides having a better understanding of the other, like in the best Trek stories.

There's a lot of hate showing up for this way too action oriented film. I agree, this seems like way too much for Trek.
But I have to say, something that I disliked very much about the last two films were how much they seemed to just take place on, or near, earth.
I craved seeing them explore to find NEW WORLDS and NEW CIVILIZATIONS and this film, finally addresses that.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment: Star Trek, at its core, was about (1) ideas, morality and what it means to be human, (2) well-defined likable characters with a lot of chemistry between them,  (3) high concept sci-fi plots with a dash of action and humor, and (4) hope for the future. The last movie was enjoyable, but it wasn't Star Trek. The problem, quite simply, is it's not clear anymore what ST is, should be, or should say, in today's society. But there's no way Paramount will let a franchise die when there's a built-in fan base and money to be made. They'll pander to whoever they have to get the asses in the seats, even if they franchise is philosophically adrift.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Movies are meant to look good through trailers. If you want to create any hope of having people be interested in your movie, you need to make a trailer that at least seems somewhat appealing to the viewer. This trailer was horribly edited. I am a filmmaker and an editor myself, and I can easily tell you that whoever made this trailer knew nothing about what they were doing. 

For one, the music. The music fits horribly for this trailer. It's not bad music, but it just doesn't help to set things up. Maybe for another one they could've done something with it. It's not necessary that they set the film up with a dark tone or something like that. The trailer should've been longer (two minutes, no less) and set up the film more.  Speaking of which, that's the second problem -  the trailer is so short. It sets up nothing about the film and only leaves the viewer confused - that's exactly how I feel right now. Granted, they shouldn't give away the entire film, like the Batman vs. Superman trailer did. But here they just didn't buff up the trailer enough. It's a complete hit and miss. And lastly, as of now, the movie just doesn't look good. The opening of the trailer could've been a buildup to something bigger, but the entire thing wound up being a bunch of random action shots that amounted to nothing. So that's why a third of the ratings are dislikes, because it is most certainly a horrible trailer.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
To all those people who are complaining about this movie, be thankful that there is even a movie that somewhat relates to Star Trek.  TMP sucked, Search for Spock wasn't great, The Final Frontier was a joke, Insurrection bombed,  Nemesis seemed like a rushed way to send off the TNG crew, then TV Shows... DS9 was a little too preachy, Enterprise mucked things up and just as it was getting good it got killed unceremoniously.  

Unfortunately Star Trek in it's original intended form is not a money maker and studios only care about money - they don't care what Roddenberry's vision was.  They aren't going to drop a dime on anything that they don't think will make money and as much as it hurts fans to admit it, the Star Trek movies prior to this JJverse reboot/refit/remake/sequel series weren't money makers and were not well received by anyone other than Trek fans which in the eyes of the studio mean limited return on investment. 

I watch the old stuff in the comfort of my home no problem and enjoy it, but I'll take these Action movies even if you could essentially replace the costumes and character names and end up with a Guardians of the Galaxy movie - which would still be awesome.

Take what you can get - or just go off and watch the Stupid looking remake of Ghostbusters with a crappy 80s Ectomobile, Stupid looking proton packs strapped onto the cast of Bridesmaid.  (Funny actresses who I do like, but I'm having a hell of a time seeing them as Ghostbusters)


Oh and if you don't like the JJverse, at least you can be satisfied that the enormously oversized Enterprise which dwarfed Galaxy class ships appears to be destroyed in this one.

Star Trek has driven technology for the last 50 years or so, the last movies despite their flaws reminded me of that feeling I got as a child when they showed the enterprise. This?! Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Judging from my guess of the plot and the handful of scenes shown, it's possible that this is the closest movie to a TOS episode we've ever seen. 

It seems as if they're exploring deep space, encounter some kind of crazy swarm that attacks the ship, and the crew ends up forced to crash-land somewhere by this mystery swarm. They run into some other unknown aliens who have suffered the same fate and with no resources have to try and figure out the mystery. Through cooperation, diplomacy, and heroic action they eventually save the day despite limited resources. That's pretty damn TOS sounding. I wouldn't be surprised though if the aliens turned out to be maybe humans from the future in some kind of weird time travel plot twist or something. Too few details given to really tell.

The music and editing makes this seem like a modern day Guardians of the Galaxy type of popcorn action film, but given the trailer's presence in front of Star Wars I'm sure they're just hyping it up for a mainstream audience. That's not the type of trailer I really wanted to see, but given the financial realities here I get it. Hopefully in a month or two once Star Wars hype dies down a bit they'll have a second extended trailer that gives a better sense of the film.

Extremely cautious about this, but actually a tiny bit optimistic as there might be a decent number of TOS elements here.

So, if I'm reading trailer lingo correctly, the Enterprise gets destroyed in the very early parts of the movie, a small team "survives" and thinking the rest of the crew is dead, tries to uncovers the big mystery of the attack. Tattoo face shows up and is probably some warrior princess, her angry uncle is the one who orchestrated the attack and secretly transported the majority of the crew of the Enterprise and is holding them hostage only to be reveled later that they are alive and ok.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
What the fuck did I just watch?
...

So I've had a few minutes to digest this; rather than anger, this trailer literally made me sad because I know for sure that no new Star Trek movie or show will ever again be made with Star Trek fans in mind. The first one was fun, but was more Star Wars than Star Trek. Into Darkness was just a mashing of previously used Star Trek ideas stuffed into remake wrapping paper and was less Star Wars and more Action Movie in Space.

I'm not afraid of change, or something new. Give me something new. But think of it like this:

What if Star Wars were made to into a dry, political drama in which Jedi were little more than diplomats being sent out on missions to settle trade route negotiations, characters with no personalities and muddled motivations were to take the place of a coherent story, and real sets and characters were to be replaced with sterile, green-screened recreations of the people and places they were meant to depict? Who the fuck would want to see that?

it's called star TREK! The morons left out the TREK!

Gene Roddenberry before he passed, there's even behind the scenes interview with him on Next Generation here on YouTube when it began, he said he wasn't sure where Next Gen would take us, but the #1 rule is there must be a Trek. It carries mankind's innate instinct to explore! to go where no man has gone before! what's out there? He set clear rules for the entire franchise the #1 rule that can't be broken is there must be a trek, exploration. I would almost believe if Gene were alive today he'd never allow this crap and the last couple crappy next gen movies to be made.

for all its flaws First Contact should have been the last, we got to see the creation of what became the federation, and took care of Borg. Gene's best villain he ever created. The early Borg were badass scary. After Gene died and the Queen introduced it "humanized" the Borg and fucked them up.


course that's my opinion.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
*Why isn't this Star Trek.. I would honestly love if you wrote your main reasons..*
-The team is back in space, at the far reaches.. (classic)
-The film takes place stranded on an alien planet (classic)
-Everyone is getting in on the adventure, instead of just Spock (classic)
-The villain is something new, and exciting instead of Human (classic)


I think the fun, action packed trailer is what ruins it for some people... granted this is our first look at the movie... the 2nd trailer for all we know might be dark, with an epic score... this is meant to grasp people seeing STAR WARS (the darkest, most epic film of the year) They want audiences to think, HEY that looks fun! I love the Star Trek films!

Star Trek Darkness (which I think is F'n amazing, and underrated) was very dark.. nothing like the fun ride we had in 2009.. this is going back to that... with Pine, and Quinto confirmed for Trek 4 I think this is a perfect time to be fun, and have a good time, while having a terrifying villain (Idris Elba looks sick awesome).. and then return to an extremely dark, extremely serious film in the sequel Star Trek 4 (Klingon war maybe?)

*The only thing I'm upset about is the absence of Alice Eve <3 Carol Marcus...* I was extremely excited to see Kirk/Carol relationship further explored (pun intended)... hopefully they say what happened to her... and bring her back for Trek 4.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
No one has any idea what Gene would say about the new movies, and in reality it wouldn't matter anyway.  I for one am grateful for Gene's original vison of "wagon train to the stars"  and his ideals of what a possible future of mankind could be.  But I also remember that Gene was the inventor, the idealist, but much other Star Trek ideas came from the writing staff and set designers.  Gene took credit for everything, just as many people's boss's take credit in the weekly meetings.  But he didn't do it all by himself.  I find it ironic how people hold such high regard for a man that couldn't even keep his dick in his pants like any respectable man/husband/father should.  There is no honor in cheating as far as I'm concerned.  
I love his ideals of a greater future,  but I could give a shit less what he'd think of what the Star Trek franchise has become.  
I'll take anything these people will dish out because behind all the action is still the basic ideals of the Federation of Planets and even though the man that invented those ideas wasn't worthy of them himself,  they are still splendid ideas.  
I also believe many people have forgotten how much cheese was in the original series.  Sure there were some great episodes in TOS, but STNG, Voyager and Enterprise were a hell of a lot better as a whole.  DS9 had great moments aside from the ignorant religious overtone.  Several of the original series movies were great, I enjoyed all of them but First Contact STNG was by far the best ST movie with The wrath of Kahn coming in a very close second, neither of which used original ideals because both used a Shakespearian base.  I guess we should just thank Shakespeare for the two best Star Trek movies!  
To end this ridiculous rant I have to say that if you naysayers don't like these movies, as is obvious by your comments,  then by all means don't fucking watch them! Stay home, put TOS on Netflix and enjoy what once was, inside your precious little bubble :P

Fuck it, i'm done with any hopes of Paramount producing anything thats actually Star Trek. Maybe stop trying so hard to make it like the MCU, stop trying to court the lowest common denominators with every movie - You've alienated the core trek fanbase with each movie and destroyed everything that makes Star Trek, Star Trek. 

No offence to the actors, who actually DO make a damn good crew, but the writing is just low-effort bollocks and the studio might as well have hired Michael fucking Bay to do it.

Comment: Epic new Star Trek trailer. It looks awesome... some Star Trek fans will be angry about that, but at least Star Trek is still alive. I completely understand the fear of popularising the franchise, but Star Trek fans have to do the sums. The new Star Trek films have increased the fanbase by between 30 to 50% which means that the films will continue to be made, however, the fanbase remains small enough that Star Trek is still the least popular of all the current cinema franchises. Don't worry Star Trek fans, the average person on the street still thinks that you are sad for liking Star Trek, which is a wonderful thing. Embrace it.  I know I do...and i say that as someone who has been a fan of the films for the last 25 years.

Title: Star Trek Beyond - Trailer (2016) - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
There are only so many times you can get away with being "just fun". I will, hand-on-heart, defend the 2009 movie to my dying day. It was fine then because they were getting a foot in the door to revamp the franchise, they gave us an enjoyable ride and set the stage for weightier, more faithful installments to come thereafter (with the whole alternate timeline idea), but now it's almost 2016 where we *do* have the kind of fun space adventures Star Trek 09 was initially making up for the lack of. Now in a world where Guardians is a huge hit with audiences, and Star Wars is returning in a couple days, it's time to let Star Trek be Star Trek. I'll go for the cast, I'll go for the action, I'll go for the visuals, I'm sure I'll even enjoy myself..

But it's time we accepted it; this isn't Star Trek and these filmmakers clearly have no interest in it being so. That's a big shame.
